        {"title": "THE SCIENCE OF PROGRESSIVE OVERLOAD", "slides": ["Progressive overload is the single most important principle in strength training. Without it, your body has no reason to adapt, grow, or get stronger. Here's how it actually works.", "Progressive overload doesn't just mean 'add more weight.' There are 5 ways to progressively overload: more weight, more reps, more sets, more time under tension, and less rest time between sets.", "A 2019 systematic review in Sports Medicine found that subjects who followed progressive overload protocols gained 58% more muscle than those who kept the same routine. Your body adapts — you must give it new stimulus.", "The practical protocol: Track every workout. Each session, try to beat your last one by ONE variable. Added 1 rep? That's progressive overload. Even 0.5kg more? That's progress. Small, consistent increases compound into massive results."], "study_ref": "Sports Medicine, 2019 — Systematic Review on Progressive Overload"},
        {"title": "THE TRUTH ABOUT MEAL TIMING AND FAT LOSS", "slides": ["Does eating after 8pm make you fat? Is intermittent fasting magic? Does meal frequency matter? Let's look at what 20+ years of metabolic research actually tells us.", "A 2022 study in Cell Metabolism found that WHEN you eat has minimal impact on fat loss compared to WHAT and HOW MUCH you eat. Total daily calories and macronutrient balance explain 90%+ of results.", "Intermittent fasting works — but not for the reasons people think. It works because it reduces your eating window, which naturally reduces calorie intake. The 'fasting state' metabolic benefit is negligible compared to the calorie effect.", "The evidence-based approach: Eat when it fits your schedule and helps you hit your calorie/protein targets. Some people do better with 2 meals, others with 5. Adherence beats theoretical optimality every single time."], "study_ref": "Cell Metabolism, 2022 — Time-Restricted Eating Study"},
        {"title": "WHY STRETCHING BEFORE LIFTING IS WRONG", "slides": ["Static stretching before heavy lifting can reduce strength output by 5-8%. A meta-analysis of 104 studies confirmed this. Yet most people still touch their toes before squatting.", "Static stretching reduces muscle-tendon stiffness, which temporarily decreases force production. You're literally making your muscles weaker right before asking them to perform.", "What to do instead: Dynamic warm-up. Leg swings, arm circles, bodyweight squats, hip circles. This raises core temperature, increases blood flow, and primes the nervous system without reducing force.", "Save static stretching for AFTER your workout or on rest days. Post-workout stretching improves flexibility without compromising performance. The order matters: dynamic before, static after."], "study_ref": "Journal of Strength and Conditioning Research, 2021 — Meta-analysis on Stretching and Performance"},
