        {"title": "HOW SLEEP DESTROYS OR BUILDS YOUR GAINS", "slides": ["A University of Chicago study restricted healthy young men to 5 hours of sleep for one week. Testosterone dropped 10-15% — equivalent to aging 10-15 years hormonally.", "Sleep deprivation impairs muscle protein synthesis by up to 18%. A study in Sleep journal found that athletes sleeping <7 hours had 1.7x higher injury rates compared to those sleeping 8+ hours.", "During deep sleep (stages 3-4), growth hormone surges — responsible for muscle repair, fat metabolism, and tissue recovery. Miss deep sleep and you miss your body's primary repair window.", "The protocol for optimal recovery: 7-9 hours in bed. Room temperature 65-68°F (18-20°C). No screens 60 min before bed. No caffeine after 2pm. Consistent sleep/wake times even on weekends. This is your cheapest performance enhancer."], "study_ref": "University of Chicago Medical Center, 2011 — Sleep and Testosterone Study"},
        {"title": "CARDIO AND MUSCLE: DO THEY CANCEL EACH OTHER OUT?", "slides": ["The 'interference effect' — cardio killing your gains — is real but massively overstated. Here's what the research actually shows about combining cardio and strength training.", "A 2022 meta-analysis found that concurrent training (cardio + lifting) reduces hypertrophy by only 5-10% compared to lifting alone. Running specifically had the most interference; cycling had the least.", "The key variables that determine interference: proximity (don't do intense cardio within 6 hours of lifting), type (low-impact beats high-impact), volume (2-3 sessions/week is fine), and nutrition (eat enough to fuel both).", "The optimal setup: Lift 3-4x/week. Do 2-3 low-moderate cardio sessions (walking, cycling, swimming) on separate days or 6+ hours apart from lifting. Eat at maintenance or slight surplus. You'll build muscle AND improve cardiovascular health."], "study_ref": "Sports Medicine, 2022 — Concurrent Training Meta-Analysis"},
