        {"title": "WHY WOMEN SHOULD LIFT HEAVY (THE SCIENCE)", "slides": ["The fear of 'getting bulky' keeps millions of women from the most effective form of exercise. The science is clear: heavy lifting transforms female bodies in the best way possible.", "Women produce 15-20x less testosterone than men. Building 'bulky' muscle without pharmaceutical help is physiologically impossible. What heavy lifting DOES: builds lean, dense muscle that creates a toned, athletic appearance.", "Benefits beyond aesthetics: A Lancet study found strength training reduces all-cause mortality risk by 23% in women. It increases bone density (critical for osteoporosis prevention), improves insulin sensitivity, and reduces depression symptoms.", "The starting protocol: Learn squat, deadlift, bench press, and row with proper form. Start light. Add 2.5-5lbs per session (linear progression). Train 3x/week. Eat adequate protein (0.7-1g/lb). Within 12 weeks you'll see visible changes and feel dramatically stronger."], "study_ref": "The Lancet, 2022 — Strength Training and Mortality in Women"},
        {"title": "HOW TO BREAK THROUGH A PLATEAU", "slides": ["Hit a plateau? Your body adapted. Here's the systematic approach to breaking through based on exercise science — not just 'try harder.'", "Step 1: Confirm it's actually a plateau. Track your lifts for 3 weeks minimum. If ZERO progress on any metric (weight, reps, sets), it's a plateau. If you gained even 1 rep, you're still progressing — stay the course.", "Step 2: Check the basics first. Sleep (7-9 hrs?), protein (0.7-1g/lb?), calories (enough to support training?), stress (manageable?). 80% of plateaus are recovery problems, not training problems.", "Step 3: Modify ONE variable at a time. Options: change rep range (if doing 8-12, try 4-6 for 4 weeks), add a set per exercise, change exercise variation (front squat instead of back squat), add a deload week. Never change everything at once — you won't know what worked."], "study_ref": "Strength and Conditioning Journal, 2022 — Periodization and Plateau Management"}
